WEBVTT


00:00.000 --> 00:06.080
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. The Elephant Man, by Tim Vickery,

00:06.740 --> 00:08.060
published by Oxford University

00:08.060 --> 00:12.260
Press, Chapter 1. The Creature in the Shop.

00:14.740 --> 00:19.200
My name is Dr. Frederick Treves. I am a doctor

00:19.200 --> 00:24.100
at the London Hospital. One day, in 1884,

00:24.100 --> 00:27.640
I saw a picture in the window of a shop

00:27.640 --> 00:31.520
near the hospital. I stopped in front of the shop

00:32.080 --> 00:36.260
and looked at the picture. At first, I felt interested.

00:37.300 --> 00:40.060
Then I felt angry. Then afraid.

00:41.260 --> 00:45.980
It was a horrible, ugly picture. There was a man

00:45.980 --> 00:48.640
in the picture, but he did not look like

00:48.640 --> 00:52.080
you and me. He did not look like a man.

00:53.040 --> 00:57.340
He looked like an elephant. I read the writing

00:57.340 --> 01:02.200
under the picture. It said, come in and see the

01:02.200 --> 01:06.540
elephant man. Two pence. I opened the door

01:06.540 --> 01:10.580
and went in. There was a man in the shop.

01:11.420 --> 01:14.800
He was a dirty man in an old coat with

01:14.800 --> 01:15.200
a cigarette

01:15.200 --> 01:21.760
in his mouth. What do you want? He asked. I'd

01:21.760 --> 01:24.700
like to see the elephant man, please, I said.

01:25.800 --> 01:30.840
The man looked at me angrily. Well, you can't, he

01:30.840 --> 01:35.360
said. The shop's closing now. You can come

01:35.360 --> 01:40.780
back tomorrow. I'm sorry, I said, but I would like

01:40.780 --> 01:44.100
to see him now. I have no time tomorrow.

01:44.100 --> 01:48.140
I have a lot of work to do, but I

01:48.140 --> 01:52.640
can give you more than two pence. The man looked

01:52.640 --> 01:53.040
at me

01:53.040 --> 01:56.820
carefully. Then he took the cigarette out of his mouth

01:56.820 --> 01:59.640
and smiled with his yellow teeth.

02:01.220 --> 02:06.360
All right, sir. He said, give me twelve pence then.

02:08.200 --> 02:11.300
I gave him the money and he opened a door

02:11.300 --> 02:14.760
at the back of the shop. We went into a

02:14.760 --> 02:19.700
little room. The room was cold and dark, and there

02:19.700 --> 02:24.420
was a horrible smell in it. A creature sat on

02:24.420 --> 02:28.260
a chair behind a table. I say a creature,

02:29.220 --> 02:32.100
because it was not a man or a woman like

02:32.100 --> 02:37.340
you or me. The creature did not move or look

02:37.340 --> 02:37.740
at us.

02:38.500 --> 02:42.660
It sat very quietly on the chair in the cold,

02:43.060 --> 02:46.660
dark, dirty room and looked at the table.

02:48.580 --> 02:52.740
The creature had a cloth over its head because of

02:52.740 --> 02:56.360
the cold. On the table in front of it,

02:56.900 --> 02:57.800
there was a dead flower.

02:59.300 --> 03:05.380
Stand up, said the shopkeeper loudly. The creature stood up

03:05.380 --> 03:09.200
slowly. It took the old cloth off its

03:09.200 --> 03:14.460
head and put it on the chair. I looked at

03:14.460 --> 03:20.140
the creature and felt sad. I am a doctor, so

03:20.140 --> 03:20.500
I know

03:20.500 --> 03:25.020
a lot about accidents and ill people. I see horrible,

03:25.020 --> 03:29.060
ugly things every day. But this creature,

03:30.080 --> 03:34.880
this thing, was the worst of all. There were no

03:34.880 --> 03:37.340
men or women in the hospital like him.

03:39.220 --> 03:44.520
He wore some old trousers, but no shirt, coat or

03:44.520 --> 03:48.060
shoes, so I could see his body very well.

03:48.980 --> 03:53.080
His head was the most interesting thing. It was very,

03:53.080 --> 03:56.180
very big, like an enormous bag

03:56.180 --> 04:00.820
with a lot of books in it. The head did

04:00.820 --> 04:04.660
not have much hair, and there was another bag of

04:04.660 --> 04:05.060
brown,

04:05.460 --> 04:10.020
dirty skin at the back of it. This skin came

04:10.020 --> 04:14.640
down below his neck. I could not see one of

04:14.640 --> 04:14.760
his

04:14.760 --> 04:19.020
eyes very well because a lot of skin came down

04:19.020 --> 04:24.180
in front of his face, too. An enormous red

04:24.180 --> 04:29.040
tooth came out of his mouth under his nose. It

04:29.040 --> 04:33.160
looked like an elephant's tooth. The mouth and

04:33.160 --> 04:37.460
nose were like holes in the face. The face could

04:37.460 --> 04:42.260
not smile or laugh or look angry or sad because

04:42.260 --> 04:42.520
the

04:42.520 --> 04:47.720
skin could not move. It was dead like an elephant's

04:47.720 --> 04:52.700
face. There were more bags of dirty skin on the

04:52.700 --> 04:57.520
front and back of the creature's body. These bags came

04:57.520 --> 05:01.180
down to his legs. The right arm was

05:01.180 --> 05:04.520
enormous, and there were bags of skin on it, too.

05:05.860 --> 05:09.100
The right hand was like a man's foot,

05:09.100 --> 05:14.220
but the left hand, the left arm and the left

05:14.220 --> 05:19.420
hand were beautiful. The left arm had wonderful

05:19.420 --> 05:23.540
skin, and the fingers of the left hand were long

05:23.540 --> 05:27.920
and beautiful. It was like a young woman's hand.

05:29.420 --> 05:35.740
Walk, Merrick! said the shopkeeper angrily. Come on quickly! Move!

05:36.860 --> 05:38.560
He hit the creature with his

05:38.560 --> 05:44.600
hand. Slowly the creature walked across the room, but he

05:44.600 --> 05:47.420
could not walk well. His legs were very

05:47.420 --> 05:51.620
big and fat, and he had a bad back. He

05:51.620 --> 05:56.680
could not walk far without a stick. All right, thank

05:56.680 --> 05:57.020
you,

05:57.020 --> 06:01.180
I said. Let him sit down. I don't want to

06:01.180 --> 06:05.480
see any more. I felt ill, and the smell in

06:05.480 --> 06:06.140
the room was

06:06.140 --> 06:12.020
very bad. Yes, sir, said the shopkeeper. Sit down, Merrick!

06:14.000 --> 06:16.460
We went out of the room and closed the door.

06:17.600 --> 06:22.060
The shopkeeper smiled at me with his yellow teeth. Wonderful,

06:22.220 --> 06:24.520
sir, isn't it? He said,

06:25.100 --> 06:29.860
the best elephant man in England. Hundreds of people come

06:29.860 --> 06:31.920
to see him, you know. Hundreds!

06:32.740 --> 06:36.700
I take him all over the country, I do. Yes,

06:37.520 --> 06:42.700
very interesting, I said. Can I sit down? Yes, sir,

06:43.080 --> 06:48.400
of course. Here's a chair. He looked at me smiling.

06:49.440 --> 06:51.600
Would you like a glass of water, sir?

06:52.600 --> 06:57.540
Yes, please, I said. Then I looked at the things

06:57.540 --> 07:01.200
in the dirty shop. There were two or three bad

07:01.200 --> 07:01.520
apples,

07:02.260 --> 07:05.280
and some old black bananas. That was all.

07:06.520 --> 07:11.480
Uh, no. No, thank you. I'm all right, I said.

07:12.580 --> 07:16.840
Did you, did you call the creature Merrick?

07:17.600 --> 07:23.440
That's right, sir. Joseph Merrick, the best elephant man in

07:23.440 --> 07:26.200
England. I take him all over the

07:26.200 --> 07:29.560
country, you know. Lots of people want to see him.

07:30.360 --> 07:34.620
Yes, I see. Do you get a lot of money?

07:35.540 --> 07:41.460
Well, sometimes we do, sir. Yes. But it's difficult, you

07:41.460 --> 07:43.540
see, sir, because of the police.

07:44.460 --> 07:48.420
The police don't like us, you see, sir. So we

07:48.420 --> 07:50.800
can't stay in a town very long.

07:51.400 --> 07:56.340
We usually move every week. Yes, I see.

07:57.360 --> 08:06.120
Well, anyway, Mr. uh, Silcox, sir. Simon Silcox? Yes, well,

08:06.420 --> 08:13.520
Mr. Silcox.

08:14.320 --> 08:19.880
I think this, uh, this man, Joseph Merrick, is very

08:19.880 --> 08:20.320
interesting,

08:21.360 --> 08:23.380
and I would like to see him at the hospital.

08:24.500 --> 08:27.400
I want to look at him more carefully, you see.

08:28.260 --> 08:33.440
Yes, sir. I see. But how can he get to

08:33.440 --> 08:36.120
the hospital? It's going to be difficult.

08:37.160 --> 08:43.180
Why, man? The hospital's not far from here. Well, yes,

08:43.300 --> 08:48.640
sir. I know. But you see, Merrick can't walk

08:48.640 --> 08:53.920
very well. He needs help. You can come with him.

08:54.860 --> 08:57.500
Do you want more money? Is that it?

08:58.220 --> 09:03.760
Well, yes, sir. I do. But you see, people are

09:03.760 --> 09:08.340
afraid of him, too. In the road, little boys

09:08.340 --> 09:12.700
always run after him and hit him. Then the police

09:12.700 --> 09:15.280
get angry because people are afraid.

09:16.380 --> 09:21.400
Sometimes they take us to prison. I see, I said.

09:22.560 --> 09:24.680
Well, how can he come to the hospital then?

09:25.420 --> 09:29.800
Bring a cab, sir, said Silcox. You can take him

09:29.800 --> 09:31.640
to the hospital in a cab.

09:42.980 --> 09:45.540
Chapter 2. The Card

09:48.060 --> 09:51.940
So next day, at seven o'clock, I came to

09:51.940 --> 09:55.620
the shop in a cab. There were not very many

09:55.620 --> 09:56.340
people in

09:56.340 --> 10:00.480
the road, because it was early in the morning. In

10:00.480 --> 10:03.200
November, it is dark at seven o'clock in the

10:03.200 --> 10:06.220
morning, and I could not see the shop very well.

10:07.040 --> 10:10.920
I waited five minutes. A postman walked past.

10:11.940 --> 10:15.120
Then the door of the shop opened, and the creature,

10:15.640 --> 10:20.220
Merrick, came out. I could not see his face or

10:20.220 --> 10:23.920
his body. He had an enormous black hat on his

10:23.920 --> 10:28.920
head, like a big box. A grey cloth came down

10:28.920 --> 10:29.180
from

10:29.180 --> 10:33.120
the hat in front of his face. There was a

10:33.120 --> 10:37.280
hole in the cloth in front of his eyes. He

10:37.280 --> 10:37.760
could see

10:37.760 --> 10:40.560
out of the hole, but I could not see him.

10:41.580 --> 10:43.880
He wore a long black coat, too.

10:44.940 --> 10:48.300
The coat began at his neck and ended at his

10:48.300 --> 10:52.000
feet, so I could not see his arms, his body,

10:52.340 --> 10:52.960
or his legs.

10:54.060 --> 10:57.620
On his feet, he wore big shoes, like old bags.

10:58.980 --> 11:01.860
He had a stick in his left hand, and he

11:01.860 --> 11:02.060
walked

11:02.060 --> 11:06.900
very slowly. I opened the door of the cab and got out.
 
11:07.840 --> 11:12.840
Good morning, Mr. Merrick. I said, can you get in?

11:12.840 --> 11:22.840
Oh, my upper steps. He said, I'm sorry. I said, I don't understand.

11:22.840 --> 11:31.840
For a minute, he stood by the door of the cab and said nothing. Then he hit the cab with his stick.

11:31.840 --> 11:38.840
Steps, he said loudly. Help me up the steps.

11:38.840 --> 11:47.840
Then I understood. There were three steps up into the cab, and he could not get up them.

11:47.840 --> 11:54.840
Yes, I see. I'm sorry, I said. Let me help you.

11:55.840 --> 12:03.840
I took his left hand and began to help him. My right hand was behind his back.

12:03.840 --> 12:13.840
I felt very strange. His left hand was like a young woman's, but his back under the coat was horrible.

12:13.840 --> 12:18.840
I could feel the bags of old skin on his back under the coat.

12:18.840 --> 12:24.840
He put one enormous foot on the first step, and then he stopped.

12:24.840 --> 12:32.840
After a minute, he moved his second foot slowly. Then he stopped and waited again.

12:32.840 --> 12:36.840
Hello, sir. Can I help you?

12:36.840 --> 12:45.840
I looked behind me. It was the postman, and behind him I could see three young boys.

12:45.840 --> 12:51.840
One of the boys laughed. The postman smiled.

12:51.840 --> 12:57.840
Is the gentleman ill? He asked. I thought quickly.

12:57.840 --> 13:09.840
Yes, but this is a lady, not a gentleman. I'm a doctor, and she's ill. Take her hand so I can help her better.

13:10.840 --> 13:17.840
The postman took Merrick's left hand, and I helped him with two hands from behind.

13:17.840 --> 13:25.840
Slowly, very slowly, Merrick went up the steps and into the cab.

13:25.840 --> 13:31.840
One boy was very near the cab. He called to his friends.

13:31.840 --> 13:39.840
Come and see this, boys! A fat lady in a black coat! And look at that enormous hat!

13:39.840 --> 13:47.840
The boys laughed. They were very near the cab, too, now. I closed the door quickly.

13:47.840 --> 13:51.840
Thank you, I said to the postman.

13:51.840 --> 13:54.840
That's all right, sir, he said.

13:54.840 --> 14:00.840
She's a strange lady, sir. Isn't she? She's ill. That's all.

14:00.840 --> 14:08.840
I said quickly. We're going to the hospital. Goodbye, and thank you.

14:08.840 --> 14:15.840
The cab drove down the road to the hospital. I looked at Merrick.

14:15.840 --> 14:19.840
That was difficult, wasn't it? I said.

14:19.840 --> 14:24.840
At first he said nothing, but then he spoke.

14:24.840 --> 14:32.840
His voice was very strange, but I listened to him carefully, and I could understand him.

14:32.840 --> 14:42.840
The steps were very difficult, he said. But most things are difficult for me.

14:42.840 --> 14:48.840
Yes, I said. Nothing is easy for you, is it?

14:48.840 --> 14:57.840
No, he said. He was very quiet for a minute. Then he said,

14:57.840 --> 15:05.840
Who are you, sir? Who am I? Oh, I'm sorry.

15:05.840 --> 15:13.840
My name is Dr. Treves. Here, this is my card.

15:13.840 --> 15:23.840
I gave him a card with my name on. Then I thought, that was no good. This man can't read.

15:23.840 --> 15:33.840
But Merrick took the card and looked at it very carefully. Then he put it in his trousers pocket.

15:33.840 --> 15:42.840
I did not talk to him very much at the hospital. I looked at his head and arms and legs and body,

15:42.840 --> 15:52.840
very carefully. Then I wrote the important things about him in a little book. A nurse helped me.

15:52.840 --> 15:59.840
Merrick looked at her sometimes, but she did not smile at him or talked to him.

15:59.840 --> 16:08.840
I think she was afraid of him. I think Merrick was afraid, too, because he was very quiet.

16:08.840 --> 16:13.840
At four o'clock, I took him back to the shop in a cab.

16:13.840 --> 16:32.840
The next day, I looked in the shop window again, but the picture was not there.

16:32.840 --> 16:39.840
Chapter 3 A Letter to the Times

16:39.840 --> 16:48.840
I did not see Merrick again for two years. Then, one day, the police found him.

16:48.840 --> 16:55.840
He had my card in his hand, so they brought him to the London hospital.

16:55.840 --> 17:04.840
He was very tired, hungry and dirty, so I put him to bed in a quiet little room.

17:04.840 --> 17:13.840
But he could not stay at the hospital. He was not ill, and of course the beds in the hospital offer ill people.

17:13.840 --> 17:19.840
We have no beds for hungry people or ugly people.

17:19.840 --> 17:28.840
I told the hospital chairman, Mr. Carr Gong, about Merrick. He listened carefully.

17:28.840 --> 17:34.840
And then he wrote a letter to the editor of the Times newspaper.

17:34.840 --> 17:44.840
From the Times, December 4, 1886, a letter to the editor.

17:44.840 --> 17:54.840
Dear sir, I am writing to you about a man in our hospital. He needs your help.

17:54.840 --> 18:01.840
His name is Joseph Merrick, and he is 27 years old.

18:01.840 --> 18:10.840
He is not ill, but he cannot go out of the hospital because he is very, very ugly.

18:10.840 --> 18:17.840
Nobody likes to look at him, and some people are afraid of him.

18:17.840 --> 18:22.840
We call him the Elephant Man.

18:22.840 --> 18:29.840
Two years ago, Merrick lived in a shop near the London hospital.

18:29.840 --> 18:35.840
For two pence, people could see him and laugh at him.

18:35.840 --> 18:48.840
One day, Dr. Frederick Treves, a hospital doctor, saw Merrick, brought him to this hospital and looked at him carefully.

18:48.840 --> 18:55.840
Dr. Treves could not help Merrick, but he gave him his card.

18:55.840 --> 19:02.840
Then the shopkeeper, Silcock, took Merrick to Belgium.

19:02.840 --> 19:06.840
A lot of people in Belgium wanted to see him.

19:06.840 --> 19:11.840
And so after a year, Merrick had 50 pounds.

19:11.840 --> 19:21.840
But then Silcock took Merrick's 50 pounds, left Merrick in Belgium, and went back to London.

19:21.840 --> 19:25.840
Merrick came back to London by himself.

19:25.840 --> 19:31.840
Everyone on the train and the ship looked at him and laughed at him.

19:31.840 --> 19:35.840
In London, the police put him in prison.

19:35.840 --> 19:43.840
But then they saw Dr. Treves's card and brought Merrick to the London hospital.

19:43.840 --> 19:48.840
This man has no money, and he cannot work.

19:48.840 --> 19:56.840
His face and body are very, very ugly, so of course many people are afraid of him.

19:56.840 --> 20:00.840
But he is a very interesting man.

20:00.840 --> 20:04.840
He can read and write, and he thinks a lot.

20:04.840 --> 20:08.840
He is a good, quiet man.

20:08.840 --> 20:16.840
Sometimes he makes things with his hands and gives them to the nurses because they are kind to him.

20:16.840 --> 20:21.840
He remembers his mother, and he has a picture of her.

20:21.840 --> 20:25.840
She was beautiful and kind, he says.

20:25.840 --> 20:28.840
But he never sees her now.

20:28.840 --> 20:33.840
She gave him to Silcock a long time ago.

20:33.840 --> 20:37.840
Can the readers of the Times help us?

20:37.840 --> 20:42.840
This man is not ill, but he needs a home.

20:42.840 --> 20:47.840
We can give him a room at the hospital, but we need some money.

20:47.840 --> 20:52.840
Please write to me at the London hospital.

20:52.840 --> 21:02.840
Yours faithfully F.C. car gom, chairman of the London hospital.

21:02.840 --> 21:07.840
The readers of the Times are very kind people.

21:07.840 --> 21:10.840
They gave us a lot of money.

21:10.840 --> 21:19.840
After one week we had 50,000 pounds, so Merrick could live in the hospital for all his life.

21:19.840 --> 21:27.840
We could give him a home.

21:27.840 --> 21:33.840
Chapter 4, Merrick's First Home

21:33.840 --> 21:38.840
We gave Merrick two rooms at the back of the hospital.

21:38.840 --> 21:43.840
One room was a bathroom, so he could have a bath every day.

21:43.840 --> 21:50.840
Soon his skin was much better, and there was no horrible smell.

21:50.840 --> 21:56.840
The second room had a bed, table and chairs.

21:56.840 --> 22:01.840
I visited him every day and talked to him.

22:01.840 --> 22:06.840
He loved reading and talking about books.

22:06.840 --> 22:15.840
At first he did not know many books, the Bible, and one or two newspapers, that's all.

22:15.840 --> 22:21.840
But I gave him some books of love stories, and he liked them very much.

22:21.840 --> 22:27.840
He read them again and again, and talked about them often.

22:27.840 --> 22:33.840
For him, the men and women in these books were alive, like you and me.

22:33.840 --> 22:36.840
He was very happy.

22:36.840 --> 22:41.840
But sometimes it was difficult for him.

22:41.840 --> 22:48.840
At first one or two people in the hospital laughed at Merrick because he was ugly.

22:48.840 --> 22:53.840
Sometimes they brought their friends to look at him.

22:53.840 --> 23:01.840
One day a new nurse came to the hospital, and nobody told her about Merrick.

23:01.840 --> 23:06.840
She took his food to his room and opened the door.

23:06.840 --> 23:08.840
Then she saw him.

23:08.840 --> 23:15.840
She screamed, dropped the food on the floor, and ran out of the room.

23:15.840 --> 23:20.840
I was very angry with the nurse and went to see Merrick.

23:20.840 --> 23:25.840
He was not happy about it, but he was not very angry.

23:25.840 --> 23:30.840
I think he felt sorry for the girl.

23:30.840 --> 23:34.840
People don't like looking at me.

23:34.840 --> 23:39.840
I know that's Dr. Treves, he said.

23:39.840 --> 23:44.840
They usually laugh or scream.

23:44.840 --> 23:49.840
Well, I don't want nurses to laugh at you, Joseph.

23:49.840 --> 23:51.840
I said angrily.

23:51.840 --> 23:54.840
I want them to help you.

23:54.840 --> 24:02.840
Thank you, Dr., he said, in his strange, slow voice.

24:02.840 --> 24:06.840
But it's not important.

24:06.840 --> 24:09.840
Everyone laughed at me.

24:09.840 --> 24:13.840
I understand that.

24:13.840 --> 24:16.840
I looked at him sadly.

24:16.840 --> 24:23.840
In his one good hand, his left hand, he had the little picture of his mother.

24:24.840 --> 24:31.840
He looked at the picture for a minute and then put it by a flower on the table.

24:31.840 --> 24:40.840
A tear ran out of his eye and down the skin of his enormous ugly face.

24:40.840 --> 24:43.840
Dr. Treves?

24:43.840 --> 24:46.840
He said slowly.

24:46.840 --> 24:55.840
You and the nurses are very kind and I'm very happy here.

24:55.840 --> 24:59.840
Thank you very much.

24:59.840 --> 25:15.840
But I know I can't stay here long and I would like to live in a lighthouse after the hospital, please.

25:15.840 --> 25:21.840
A lighthouse or a home for blind people?

25:21.840 --> 25:27.840
I think those are the best places for me.

25:27.840 --> 25:29.840
What do you mean?

25:29.840 --> 25:30.840
I asked.

25:30.840 --> 25:33.840
Why?

25:33.840 --> 25:35.840
He did not look at me.

25:35.840 --> 25:42.840
He put the flower on the picture and looked at it carefully.

25:42.840 --> 25:48.840
The light houses have seen all around them, don't they?

25:48.840 --> 25:50.840
He said.

25:50.840 --> 25:59.840
Nobody could look at me in a lighthouse, so I would be happy there.

25:59.840 --> 26:09.840
And blind people can see nothing, so they couldn't see me, could they?

26:09.840 --> 26:14.840
But Joseph, I said, this is your home.

26:14.840 --> 26:17.840
You live here now.

26:17.840 --> 26:21.840
You aren't going to leave the hospital.

26:21.840 --> 26:25.840
Not today, perhaps.

26:25.840 --> 26:27.840
He said.

26:27.840 --> 26:38.840
But soon you are a kind man, Dr. Treves, but I can't stay here very long.

26:38.840 --> 26:42.840
I have no money.

26:42.840 --> 26:44.840
I smiled.

26:44.840 --> 26:50.840
Joseph, I said, this is your home now.

26:50.840 --> 26:52.840
Don't you understand?

26:52.840 --> 26:57.840
You can stay here all your life.

26:57.840 --> 27:05.840
Very carefully, I told him about the letter to the times and the money.

27:06.840 --> 27:13.840
I don't think he understood at first, so I told him again.

27:13.840 --> 27:16.840
He was very quiet for a minute.

27:16.840 --> 27:22.840
Then he stood up and walked up and down the room very quickly.

27:22.840 --> 27:28.840
A strange sound came from him, like laughing.

27:35.840 --> 27:45.840
Chapter 5, An Important Visitor

27:45.840 --> 27:52.840
I did not want Merrick to live by himself, like a man in the lighthouse.

27:52.840 --> 27:59.840
He read his books and talked to me, but I wanted him to talk to more people,

27:59.840 --> 28:03.840
and I wanted him to talk to women.

28:04.840 --> 28:11.840
Merrick read about women in his books, but he did not often talk to women.

28:11.840 --> 28:17.840
He met the nurses every day, but they did not talk to him very much.

28:17.840 --> 28:23.840
For them, he was always a creature, not a man.

28:23.840 --> 28:30.840
One day, one of my friends, a beautiful young woman, came to the hospital.

28:30.840 --> 28:35.840
I told her about Merrick and took her to his room.

28:35.840 --> 28:40.840
She opened the door and smiled at him.

28:40.840 --> 28:44.840
Good morning, Mr. Merrick, she said.

28:44.840 --> 28:47.840
Then she shook his hand.

28:47.840 --> 28:52.840
Merrick looked at her for a minute with his mouth open.

28:52.840 --> 28:59.840
Then he sat down on his bed with his head in his hand and cried.

28:59.840 --> 29:02.840
He cried for nearly five minutes.

29:02.840 --> 29:10.840
The tears ran down his face between his fingers and onto the floor.

29:10.840 --> 29:16.840
My friend sat on the bed beside him and put her hand on his arm.

29:16.840 --> 29:25.840
She said nothing, but she smiled at him and shook his hand again before she left.

29:25.840 --> 29:28.840
Dr. Treves?

29:28.840 --> 29:31.840
He said to me that night.

29:31.840 --> 29:35.840
That lady was wonderful.

29:35.840 --> 29:46.840
My mother smiled at me once, many years ago, but no women smile at me now.

29:47.840 --> 29:55.840
But this lady smiled at me too, and she shook my hand.

29:55.840 --> 30:03.840
A beautiful lady smiled at me and shook my hand.

30:03.840 --> 30:13.840
My young lady friend came again the next week and talked to Merrick for half an hour.

30:13.840 --> 30:18.840
The week after that she came again with a friend.

30:18.840 --> 30:23.840
They gave him some books and had a cup of tea with him.

30:23.840 --> 30:26.840
It was wonderful for him.

30:26.840 --> 30:31.840
For the first time in his life he had some friends.

30:31.840 --> 30:34.840
He was a very happy man.

30:34.840 --> 30:42.840
He sat in his room and read his books and said no more about living on a lighthouse.

30:43.840 --> 30:50.840
People began to read about Merrick in the newspapers so he had a lot of visitors.

30:50.840 --> 30:53.840
Everybody wanted to see him.

30:53.840 --> 30:58.840
A lot of important ladies and gentlemen visited him.

30:58.840 --> 31:04.840
They smiled at him, shook his hand and gave him books.

31:04.840 --> 31:11.840
Merrick liked talking to these people, and he began to forget about his ugly body.

31:11.840 --> 31:15.840
His visitors never laughed at him.

31:15.840 --> 31:20.840
He began to feel like a man, not a creature.

31:20.840 --> 31:28.840
One wonderful day a very important lady came to the hospital to visit him.

31:28.840 --> 31:33.840
I met the lady and took her to his room.

31:33.840 --> 31:38.840
Then I opened the door and smiled at him.

31:38.840 --> 31:42.840
Good morning, Joseph, I said.

31:42.840 --> 31:49.840
There is a new visitor to see you today, a very famous lady.

31:49.840 --> 31:53.840
Merrick stood up beside his table.

31:53.840 --> 32:00.840
He did not smile because his face could not smile, but his eyes looked happy.

32:00.840 --> 32:04.840
That's good, he said.

32:04.840 --> 32:07.840
Who is it?

32:07.840 --> 32:12.840
I moved away from the door and the visitor walked in.

32:12.840 --> 32:18.840
Your Majesty, this is Joseph Merrick, I said.

32:18.840 --> 32:27.840
Joseph, this is her Majesty, Queen Alexandra, the Queen of England.

32:27.840 --> 32:31.840
Queen Alexandra smiled at him.

32:31.840 --> 32:34.840
How do you do, Mr. Merrick?

32:34.840 --> 32:38.840
She said, I'm very pleased to meet you.

32:38.840 --> 32:42.840
Then she shook his hand.

32:42.840 --> 32:45.840
Merrick did not move.

32:45.840 --> 32:52.840
For nearly half a minute he stood and looked at her with his mouth open.

32:52.840 --> 32:58.840
Then he spoke in his strange, slow voice.

32:58.840 --> 33:00.840
How?

33:00.840 --> 33:05.840
How do you do your Majesty?

33:05.840 --> 33:07.840
He said.

33:07.840 --> 33:15.840
But I don't think the Queen understood him because he tried to get down on his knees at the same time.

33:15.840 --> 33:21.840
It was very difficult for him because of his enormous legs.

33:21.840 --> 33:24.840
No, please, Mr. Merrick.

33:24.840 --> 33:27.840
Do get up, said the Queen.

33:27.840 --> 33:30.840
I would like to talk to you.

33:30.840 --> 33:34.840
Can we sit at your table?

33:34.840 --> 33:36.840
Yes.

33:36.840 --> 33:40.840
Yes, of course, he said.

33:40.840 --> 33:43.840
They sat at the table.

33:43.840 --> 33:48.840
She took his left hand, the good hand, in hers.

33:48.840 --> 33:55.840
She looked at the hand carefully and then smiled at Merrick again.

33:55.840 --> 34:00.840
I often read about you in the newspapers, she said.

34:00.840 --> 34:05.840
You are a very interesting man, Mr. Merrick.

34:05.840 --> 34:11.840
You have a very difficult life, but people say you're happy.

34:11.840 --> 34:13.840
Is it true?

34:13.840 --> 34:16.840
Are you happy now?

34:16.840 --> 34:19.840
Oh, yes, your Majesty.

34:19.840 --> 34:22.840
Yes, said Merrick.

34:22.840 --> 34:26.840
I'm a very happy man.

34:26.840 --> 34:33.840
I have a home here now and friends and my books.

34:33.840 --> 34:39.840
I'm happy every hour of the day.

34:39.840 --> 34:43.840
What a wonderful story, she said.

34:43.840 --> 34:46.840
I'm very pleased to hear it.

34:46.840 --> 34:51.840
Now, tell me about your reading.

34:51.840 --> 34:55.840
I see you have a lot of books here.

34:55.840 --> 34:59.840
Oh, yes, your Majesty.

34:59.840 --> 35:04.840
I love my books, said Merrick.

35:04.840 --> 35:11.840
And for nearly half an hour, they sat and talked about books.

35:11.840 --> 35:19.840
The Queen gave him a little book and some read flowers before she left.

35:19.840 --> 35:24.840
After her visit, Merrick began to sing.

35:24.840 --> 35:29.840
He could not sing easily, of course, because of his mouth,

35:29.840 --> 35:36.840
but all that day there was a strange, happy noise in his room.

35:36.840 --> 35:43.840
He looked at the flowers carefully and put them on his table.

35:43.840 --> 35:52.840
He had many visits from the Queen, and at Christmas she sent him a Christmas card.

35:52.840 --> 35:59.840
Windsor Castle, the 20th of December, 1888.

36:00.840 --> 36:07.840
Dear Joseph, here is a small Christmas present for you.

36:07.840 --> 36:11.840
I think it looks like me, doesn't it?

36:11.840 --> 36:20.840
I do like visiting you very much, and I am going to come to the hospital again in the new year.

36:20.840 --> 36:27.840
Happy Christmas, your friend, Alexandra.

36:27.840 --> 36:33.840
The present was a picture of Queen Alexandra with her name on it.

36:33.840 --> 36:40.840
Merrick cried over it and put it carefully by the bed in his room.

36:40.840 --> 36:45.840
Then he sat down and wrote a letter to the Queen.

36:45.840 --> 36:50.840
It was the first letter of his life.

36:51.840 --> 36:59.840
The London Hospital, 23rd of December, 1888.

36:59.840 --> 37:11.840
My dear Queen, thank you very, very much for your wonderful card and the beautiful picture.

37:11.840 --> 37:21.840
It is the best thing in my room, the very best, the most beautiful thing I have.

37:21.840 --> 37:29.840
This is the first Christmas in my life, and my first Christmas present.

37:29.840 --> 37:38.840
Perhaps I had a Christmas with my mother once, but I do not remember it.

37:38.840 --> 37:46.840
I have my mother's picture too, and she is beautiful like you.

37:46.840 --> 37:57.840
But now I know many famous ladies and kind people like Dr. Treves, and I am a very happy man.

37:57.840 --> 38:05.840
I am happy too, because I am going to see you in the new year.

38:05.840 --> 38:26.840
Happy Christmas to you, my dear friend, with all my love, Joseph Merrick.

38:27.840 --> 38:34.840
Chapter 6 Outside the Hospital

38:34.840 --> 38:41.840
Merrick had a lot of friends now, but he was more like a child than a man.

38:41.840 --> 38:50.840
He could read about things and talk to his visitors, but he could not go out of the hospital by himself.

38:50.840 --> 38:55.840
He thought and played like a child.

38:55.840 --> 39:00.840
After Christmas, he wanted to go to the theatre.

39:00.840 --> 39:07.840
This was very difficult, because I did not want the people in the theatre to see him.

39:07.840 --> 39:13.840
But a kind lady from the theatre, Mrs. Kendall, helped us.

39:13.840 --> 39:19.840
We bought tickets for a box at the side of the theatre.

39:19.840 --> 39:29.840
We went to the theatre in a cab with dark windows, and we went into the theatre by a door at the back, the Queen's door.

39:29.840 --> 39:32.840
Nobody saw us.

39:32.840 --> 39:40.840
Three nurses sat at the front of the box, and Merrick and I sat in the dark behind them.

39:40.840 --> 39:47.840
Nobody in the theatre could see us, but we could see the play.

39:47.840 --> 39:52.840
It was a children's Christmas play. Merrick loved it.

39:52.840 --> 39:56.840
It was a most wonderful, exciting story.

39:56.840 --> 40:03.840
Often he laughed, and sometimes he tried to sing like the children in the theatre.

40:03.840 --> 40:11.840
He was like a child. For him, everything in the story was true.

40:11.840 --> 40:18.840
Once he was very afraid, because the bad man in the play was angry and had a knife.

40:18.840 --> 40:24.840
At first, Merrick wanted to leave the theatre, but I stopped him.

40:24.840 --> 40:30.840
Then he was very angry with this bad man in the play.

40:30.840 --> 40:38.840
He hit his hand on his chair and stood up and talked to the man, but nobody heard him.

40:38.840 --> 40:44.840
When the bad man went to prison, Merrick laughed.

40:44.840 --> 40:49.840
Merrick thought the beautiful young lady in the play was wonderful.

40:49.840 --> 40:52.840
He wanted to talk to her, too.

40:52.840 --> 41:00.840
At the end of the play, he was very happy, because she married a good young man.

41:00.840 --> 41:08.840
He remembered this play for a long time, and he talked a lot about the people in it.

41:08.840 --> 41:15.840
What do you think they did after we left? He asked me.

41:15.840 --> 41:21.840
Where do the young lady and the young man live?

41:21.840 --> 41:24.840
What are they doing now?

41:24.840 --> 41:30.840
I don't know, I said. Perhaps they live in the country.

41:30.840 --> 41:34.840
Merrick thought about this for a long time.

41:34.840 --> 41:44.840
Then he said, Dr. Treves, can I go to the country, please?

41:44.840 --> 41:52.840
I saw the country once from a train, but I never went there.

41:52.840 --> 42:05.840
I often read about it in books. It's very beautiful, isn't it? I would like to see it.

42:05.840 --> 42:13.840
The visit to the theatre was difficult, but a visit to the country was more difficult.

42:13.840 --> 42:18.840
But again, one of his new friends helped us.

42:18.840 --> 42:26.840
She had a small house in the country, and Merrick could stay in it for the summer, she said.

42:26.840 --> 42:34.840
I took Merrick to the country in a train with dark windows, so nobody could see him.

42:34.840 --> 42:38.840
Then we went in a cab to the country house.

42:38.840 --> 42:45.840
There were a lot of trees near the house, but no people lived near it.

42:45.840 --> 42:52.840
A countryman brought food to the house every day, but no people came near it.

42:52.840 --> 43:00.840
I stayed with him that night. At night, it was very dark and quiet.

43:00.840 --> 43:09.840
In the morning, hundreds of birds sang in the trees, and everything outside the house was green.

43:10.840 --> 43:20.840
Merrick walked under the big trees, looking at things happily, and singing his strange song.

43:20.840 --> 43:29.840
I went back to London, but Merrick stayed there for six weeks. He was wonderfully happy.

43:29.840 --> 43:34.840
Every week he wrote me a letter.

43:34.840 --> 43:47.840
Apple Tree House, West Wickham, Berkshire, the 21st of July, 1889.

43:47.840 --> 43:55.840
Dear Dr. Trees, I had a wonderful day again today.

43:55.840 --> 44:04.840
It was very warm, so I walked under the trees and sat by a stream.

44:04.840 --> 44:11.840
The water in the stream made a beautiful noise, like singing.

44:11.840 --> 44:18.840
Did you know that? I listened to it for two hours.

44:18.840 --> 44:28.840
Lots of little birds came near me. One had a red body in front and a brown back.

44:28.840 --> 44:39.840
I gave it some bread, and it sat on my hand. A lot of birds are my friends now.

44:39.840 --> 44:50.840
I watched the fish in the stream too. They were very exciting because they moved very fast.

44:50.840 --> 44:57.840
One minute they were there, and the next minute I couldn't see them.

44:57.840 --> 45:03.840
But I waited quietly, and they always came back.

45:04.840 --> 45:11.840
I put my hand in the water, but I couldn't touch them.

45:11.840 --> 45:21.840
I met a big dog yesterday. It made a very loud noise, but I was not afraid.

45:21.840 --> 45:30.840
I sat down quietly and looked at it, and it came and smelt my hand.

45:30.840 --> 45:39.840
I saw it again today and gave it some bread. It likes me now.

45:39.840 --> 45:45.840
I am going to put some flowers from the country in this letter.

45:45.840 --> 45:51.840
There are hundreds of flowers here. Did you know that?

45:51.840 --> 45:59.840
I like the little blue ones best, but they are all beautiful.

45:59.840 --> 46:06.840
I have lots of them in my room. I give them water every morning.

46:06.840 --> 46:15.840
Little flowers are very thirsty, you know. I am very happy here, doctor,

46:15.840 --> 46:27.840
but I want to see you again soon too, with love from your friend Joseph Merrick.

46:27.840 --> 46:32.840
At the end of the summer he came back to London.

46:32.840 --> 46:37.840
He was very well, and his skin looked much better.

46:37.840 --> 46:54.840
He talked about the country a lot, but he was happy to see his friends and his books again too.

46:54.840 --> 47:00.840
Chapter 7 The Last Letter

47:00.840 --> 47:09.840
Six months later, in April 1890, I found him dead in bed.

47:09.840 --> 47:15.840
He was on his back in bed, so at first I thought he was asleep.

47:15.840 --> 47:20.840
I talked to him, but he did not move.

47:20.840 --> 47:28.840
Then I saw that the skin on his face was blue, so I knew he was dead.

47:28.840 --> 47:34.840
He did not usually sleep on his back. His enormous head was very heavy,

47:34.840 --> 47:42.840
so he usually sat up in bed with his arms round his legs and his head on his knees.

47:42.840 --> 47:49.840
He could sleep well like this, but he wanted to sleep on his back like you and me.

47:49.840 --> 47:58.840
He tried to sleep on his back that night, but his heavy head came off the bed and he broke his neck.

47:58.840 --> 48:02.840
He died very quickly.

48:02.840 --> 48:12.840
Next day, the chairman of the London hospital, Mr. Carr Gom, wrote to the editor of The Times again.

48:12.840 --> 48:18.840
The Times, April the 16th, 1890.

48:18.840 --> 48:29.840
Dear Sir, three and a half years ago, I wrote to you about a man called Joseph Merrick.

48:29.840 --> 48:38.840
This man was called the Elephant Man, because he was born with a very ugly body.

48:38.840 --> 48:46.840
Merrick was not ill, but he could not work, and he had no money.

48:46.840 --> 48:54.840
The readers of The Times felt sorry for him, and they gave me a lot of money for Merrick.

48:54.840 --> 49:01.840
Because of this money, we could give Merrick a home in the London hospital.

49:01.840 --> 49:09.840
It was his first good home, and for three and a half years, he lived here happily.

49:09.840 --> 49:17.840
The doctors and nurses of the hospital helped him, and many important people visited him.

49:17.840 --> 49:27.840
He read many books, he went to the theatre, and in the summer, he stayed in the country for six weeks.

49:27.840 --> 49:34.840
Because of your reader's money, we could give him a happy life.

49:34.840 --> 49:41.840
Last night, Joseph Merrick died quietly in his bed.

49:41.840 --> 49:51.840
He was a man with a very ugly body, but he was a good, kind man, and he had a lot of friends.

49:51.840 --> 49:57.840
We like to talk to him, and we are all very sorry because he is dead.

49:57.840 --> 50:03.840
A lot of people are going to remember him for a long time.

50:03.840 --> 50:09.840
There is some money left, so I am going to give it to the hospital.

50:09.840 --> 50:12.840
Thank you, sir, for your help.

50:12.840 --> 50:20.840
Yours faithfully FC Kargom, Chairman of the London hospital.

